  "opinion": "As a mechanic in New York who's been around the block a few times, I've learned that fake content on social media is like a bad engine—sometimes it'll just run smoothly until it suddenly sputters and leaves you in a mess. I spend a few times a week on social media, mostly checking my old photos from volunteering at the community center and sharing some of my photography with friends. My parents taught me that trust is built slowly, one honest conversation at a time, so I've always been careful to verify information before sharing it. When I see something that seems off—like a video that looks too good to be true or a post that's missing key details—I stop and ask myself: 'Would this make sense to a mechanic?' or 'Does this align with what I know about how things work?' For example, a few years ago, I saw a post claiming a new oil change could fix a car for $10. That didn't sound right, and it turned out to be a scam. I reported it and shared my experience with the community group I volunteer with. Being a high extraversion person, I love connecting with others, so I've made it a habit to talk to friends about these things instead of just deleting them. It's important to stay open but not too trusting—like checking a car engine, you need to know what's really going on before you fix it. My neuroticism level keeps me on my toes, so I don't get too upset when I find fake content but I do take steps to keep it from spreading.",
